Cell membrane transport refers to the movement of molecules across the cell membrane, which is selectively permeable, meaning it allows certain molecules to pass through while keeping others out. There are two main types of cell membrane transport: passive transport and active transport.

Passive transport occurs without the use of energy. It involves the movement of molecules from an area of high concentration to an area of low concentration, down their concentration gradient. This movement occurs until equilibrium is reached, meaning the concentration of molecules is the same on both sides of the membrane.

There are two types of passive transport: diffusion and osmosis.

Diffusion is the random movement of molecules from an area of high concentration to an area of low concentration. This movement occurs in a gas or liquid and is driven by the kinetic energy of the molecules. For example, when you open a bottle of perfume, the fragrance molecules diffuse out of the bottle and spread into the air.

Osmosis is a type of diffusion that involves the movement of water molecules through a selectively permeable membrane from an area of high concentration to an area of low concentration. This movement helps to equalize the concentration of solutes on both sides of the membrane. For example, if you have a solution of sugar in water on one side of a membrane and water on the other side, the water molecules will move from the side with a higher concentration of water (the side with the sugar solution) to the side with a lower concentration of water (the other side) until the concentration of solutes is the same on both sides.

Active transport, on the other hand, requires energy to move molecules against their concentration gradient, from an area of low concentration to an area of high concentration. Passive Transport: This is like the lazy river at a water park—it doesn't require energy from the cell. It includes two subtypes:



a. Simple Diffusion: Imagine a room with a partition, and you spray perfume on one side. Eventually, the perfume molecules will spread evenly throughout the room. In a cell, this is when molecules move from an area of high concentration to an area of low concentration through the cell membrane. No energy is needed.



b. Facilitated Diffusion: Sometimes, larger molecules or charged ions need help to cross the cell membrane. Think of this as having special channels or doors (proteins) that allow specific molecules to pass through. Still, no energy is used.



Active Transport: This is like pumping water uphill—it requires energy (usually from ATP). There are two main types:



a. Primary Active Transport: In this process, a protein pump actively moves molecules against their concentration gradient, from low to high concentration. The sodium-potassium pump is a classic example of primary active transport.



b. Secondary Active Transport: Here, energy is indirectly used. It relies on the energy created by primary active transport to move other substances against their concentration gradient. One common example is the sodium-glucose transporter in the intestine.
